    title2: "1440. When is a driver required to drive on the “hard shoulder” - where the “shoulder” is asphalt-paved and free of traffic - in order to allow another vehicle to overtake him?",
    link3: "",
    guid: "",
    description4: "<div dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: left\"><ul><li><span>When the vehicle drives very slowely for any reason.</span></li><li><span>Only when the vehicle is forced to drive slowly on a steep uphill climb, and disturbs the free traffic.</span></li><li><span id=\"correctAnswer1440\">When a driver of a motor vehicle is forced to drive very slowly due to the freight he’s carrying or to the steepness of the road, and he delays the traffic behind him.</span></li><li><span>Never. It is prohibited to drive on the “hard shoulders”; hence, a vehicle that delays the traffic behind it should pull into the “hard shoulder” and stop, to allow the traffic congestion behind him to open up. </span></li></ul><div dir=\"ltr\" style=\"text-align: right;padding-top: 4px;\"><span>| «C1» | «C» | </span><span style=\"float: left;\"><button type=\"button\" onclick=\"var correctAnswer=document.getElementById('correctAnswer1440');correctAnswer.style.background='yellow'\">Correct Answer</button></span></div></div>",
